ce:section.ce:para:
The enhanced RRS signal is often located in the lower energy region of resonance absorption rather than exactly corresponding to the characteristic absorption band of its molecule. Therefore, RRS spectra can be obtained by scanning using a fluorescence spectrophotometer with excitation and emission monochromators. The excitation wavelength is set equal to the emission wavelength (Δλ = λem-λex = 0). The intensity of the RRS signal is mainly derived from the scattering of excitation light by nanoparticles and the SPR effect. The change in particle concentration, aggregation degree, and particle size in the system will cause the signal change. Two RRS resonance peaks exist at 375 and 520 nm for the Pb2+ -Apt- CDN -Fuc- HAuCl4 analysis system (Fig. 3
                        ), and two RRS resonance peaks at 375 and 530 nm for the AsO2 
                        −-Apt- CDN -Fuc- HAuCl4 analysis system (Figure S3). which are attributed to the catalytic generation of AuNPs by CDs. The peak at 375 nm had better reproducibility, so it was selected for measurement. The sensitivity of the RRS analysis platform in this article was lower than that of the SERS analysis platform.
